com.siperian.sif.message.mrm

Class DeleteRequest

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.siperian.sif.message.SiperianRequest
      • com.siperian.sif.message.SiperianObjectRequest
        • com.siperian.sif.message.mrm.DeleteRequest
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    SiperianObjectUidProvider, Serializable

    public class DeleteRequest
extends SiperianObjectRequest
    Represents a request object to delete the specified records from the MDM Hub. You can delete a base object record and all its cross-reference (XREF) records or any specific XREF record. When a XREF record is deleted, the state of the base object record is reset to its XREF record's state that has higher precedence. The descending order of precedence for the states is ACTIVE, PENDING, and DELETED. When the records are deleted, the records undergo the following changes:
    • Records in the ACTIVE state are set to the DELETED state.
    • Records in the PENDING state are hard deleted.
    • Records in the DELETED state are retained in the DELETED state.

    For example, record A has two XREF records that are in the ACTIVE state. The state of record A is ACTIVE. If you delete one of the XREF records, the record A has one XREF record in the ACTIVE state and another XREF record in the DELETED state. The state of record A after the delete operation is ACTIVE because the ACTIVE state has higher precedence over the DELETED state. If you again delete the XREF record in the ACTIVE state, the state of record A changes to the DELETED state because both the XREF records are in the DELETED state.

    Usage Example
    The following example deletes the XREF record that has 1234 as the source key and CRM as the system name:

    DeleteRequest request = new DeleteRequest();
    RecordKey recordKey = new RecordKey();
    recordKey.setSourceKey("1234");
    recordKey.setSystemName("CRM");
    ArrayList recordKeys = new ArrayList();
    recordKeys.add(recordKey);
    request.setRecordKeys(recordKeys); // Required
    request.setSiperianObjectUid("PACKAGE.CUSTOMER_UPDATE"); //Required

    DeleteResponse response = (DeleteResponse) sipClient.process(request);

    See Also:
    DeleteResponse, Serialized Form

      • getRecordKeys

        public List getRecordKeys()
        Gets the list of keys that uniquely identify the records to delete.
        Returns:
        List of keys that uniquely identify the records.

      • setRecordKeys

        public void setRecordKeys(List recordKeys)
        Sets the list of keys that uniquely identify the records to delete. If you specify the RowID of a record as the key, the deleteBORecord parameter in the setDeleteBORecord(boolean) method is automatically set to true, and the base object record and all its XREF records are deleted. To delete the base object record and all its XREF records, the user must have the DELETE privilege on the base object record.
        Parameters:
        recordKeys - List of keys that uniquely identify the records.

      • isDeleteBORecord

        public boolean isDeleteBORecord()
        Indicates whether to delete the base object record and all its XREF records or only the specified records.
        Returns:
        • True to delete the base object record and all its XREF records.
        • False to delete only the specified records.

      • setDeleteBORecord

        public void setDeleteBORecord(boolean deleteBORecord)
        Sets the status to indicate whether to delete the base object record and all its XREF records or only the specified records. To delete the base object record and all its XREF records, the user must have the DELETE privilege on the base object record. This method overrides the value that you set in the setRecordKeys(List) method.
        Parameters:
        deleteBORecord - Indicates whether to delete the base object record and all its XREF records or only the specified records. Specify true to delete the base object record and all its XREF records, or specify false to delete only the specified records. Default is false.

      • isDeleteAsSMOS

        public boolean isDeleteAsSMOS()
        Indicates whether to use the state management override system.
        Returns:
        • True to use the state management override system.
        • False to not use the state management override system.

      • setDeleteAsSMOS

        public void setDeleteAsSMOS(boolean deleteAsSMOS)
        Sets the status to indicate whether to use the state management override system. The state management override system is a source system that can override the state of records from other source systems and mark the state of records as DELETED.
        Overrides:
        setDeleteAsSMOS in class SiperianRequest
        Parameters:
        deleteAsSMOS - Indicates whether to use the state management override system. Specify true to use the state management override system, or specify false to not use the state management override system. Default is false.
